#!hexa strict
// qmirror/mabk-ardehali/module/mabk_ardehali.hexa
//
// Mermin-Ardehali-Belinskii-Klyshko (MABK) multipartite Bell inequality —
// EXACT 2^N-amplitude UNITARY + projective reproduction of the canonical
// MABK Bell functional on N ∈ {3, 4, 5, 6} parties, evaluated on the
// N-party GHZ state with the optimal Mermin X/Y measurement strategy.
// Verifies the famous EXPONENTIAL quantum-over-LHV violation
//     |B_N|^GHZ = 2^{(N-1)/2}  vs  |B_N|^LHV <= 1
// (Werner-Wolf normalisation; LHV bound forced to 1 by construction).
//
// @tool(slug="qmirror_mabk_ardehali", desc="Mermin-Ardehali-Belinskii-Klyshko (MABK) multipartite Bell inequality on N in {3,4,5,6} parties (Mermin 1990 PRL 65 1838; Ardehali 1992 PRA 46 5375; Belinskii-Klyshko 1993; Werner-Wolf 2001 PRA 64 032112; Abiuso 2025 arXiv:2503.03878 RG-tight self-testing framing if reachable). Builds the BK recursive Bell operator M_N (with M_1=X, M_1'=Y, M_N=(1/2)[M_{N-1}(X_N+Y_N)+M_{N-1}'(X_N-Y_N)], M_N'=(1/2)[M_{N-1}'(X_N+Y_N)-M_{N-1}(X_N-Y_N)]) by expanding into 2^N signed Pauli strings sigma_{s_1}..sigma_{s_N} with s_i in {X,Y}; constructs |GHZ_N> via H_0 + chained CNOTs on the pure-hexa engine_aer state-vector kernel; computes <GHZ_N|M_N|GHZ_N> exactly via per-string state-vector evolution + inner product (Born). Brute-forces the LHV bound by enumerating ALL 2^{2N} deterministic +-1 assignments (a_i, a_i' in {+1,-1}) using a bit-mask + popcount fast path (zero array allocation in the hot loop -- critical because the 0.1.0-dispatch interpreter does not GC boxed numeric temporaries inside long while loops) and confirms max_a |M_N(a)| = 1 exactly. Verifies the exponential violation ratio Q_N = 2^{(N-1)/2} (sqrt2, 2, 2sqrt2, 4 for N=3..6). NOT a duplicate of chsh (CHSH = N=2 MABK with ratio sqrt2); NOT of ghz_mermin (the latter is the all-or-nothing Mermin contradiction on a fixed 4-basis witness). Pure-hexa exact engine, engine_aer external signature untouched (@D g7). Falsifier-first marker (@D g6).")
// @usage(hexa run qmirror/mabk-ardehali/module/mabk_ardehali.hexa --selftest)
// @sentinel(__QMIRROR_MABK_ARDEHALI__ <PASS|FAIL>)
// @resolver-bypass(reason="Pure-hexa exact 2^N (N<=6) state-vector + analytic Born + deterministic LHV brute force; no qiskit, no python bridge, no subprocess for the physics.")
//
// ── Paper deep-dive (the citation chain) ───────────────────────────────
//
//   [1] N. David Mermin, "Extreme quantum entanglement in a superposition
//       of macroscopically distinct states", Phys. Rev. Lett. 65, 1838
//       (1990). DOI 10.1103/PhysRevLett.65.1838.
//       --> the original N-party Mermin inequality on the GHZ state.
//           Eq.(4) of [1] gives the all-or-nothing Mermin polynomial
//                F_N = (1/2i)[ (sigma_x^{(1)} + i sigma_y^{(1)}) ⊗ ...
//                           ⊗ (sigma_x^{(N)} + i sigma_y^{(N)})
//                            -  (sigma_x^{(1)} - i sigma_y^{(1)}) ⊗ ...
//                           ⊗ (sigma_x^{(N)} - i sigma_y^{(N)}) ]
//           which expands into a signed sum of length-N Pauli strings
//           with an odd number of sigma_y factors. Mermin's headline
//           result (Eq.5): on the GHZ state |GHZ_N>, <F_N> = 2^{N-1};
//           the LHV bound (for the same polynomial) is 2^{(N-1)/2} for
//           odd N and 2^{N/2} for even N. The exponential quantum/LHV
//           gap ~ 2^{(N-1)/2} for odd N is the famous "extreme quantum
//           entanglement" of the title.
//
//   [2] Mohammad Ardehali, "Bell inequalities with a magnitude of
//       violation that grows exponentially with the number of particles",
//       Phys. Rev. A 46, 5375 (1992). DOI 10.1103/PhysRevA.46.5375.
//       --> extends Mermin's N-odd construction of [1] to ALL N by
//           introducing the second-observable (the "primed" observable
//           A_N' at the last party) chosen along a different equatorial
//           direction. Establishes that the exponential 2^{(N-1)/2}
//           violation holds for every N >= 2.
//
//   [3] A. V. Belinskii and D. N. Klyshko, "Interference of light and
//       Bell's theorem", Usp. Fiz. Nauk 163, 1 (1993); Phys.-Usp. 36,
//       653 (1993). DOI 10.1070/PU1993v036n08ABEH002299.
//       --> reformulates Mermin-Ardehali as the recursive operator now
//           known as the Belinskii-Klyshko (BK) operator (also Mermin-
//           Klyshko, MK; sometimes just MABK):
//                M_1 = A_1,   M_1' = A_1'
//                M_N   = (1/2) [ M_{N-1}  ⊗ (A_N + A_N') +
//                                M_{N-1}' ⊗ (A_N - A_N') ]
//                M_N'  = (1/2) [ M_{N-1}' ⊗ (A_N + A_N') -
//                                M_{N-1}  ⊗ (A_N - A_N') ]
//           In this normalisation the LHV bound on |<M_N>| is EXACTLY 1
//           (i.e. the (1/2) factor at each recursion step exactly cancels
//           the doubling of the LHV bound), and the quantum maximum
//           is 2^{(N-1)/2}, saturated on the N-party GHZ state with
//           A_i = X, A_i' = Y. This is the normalisation used by this
//           module (and by Werner-Wolf [4] as "Eq. (1)").
//
//   [4] R. F. Werner and M. M. Wolf, "All-multipartite Bell-correlation
//       inequalities for two dichotomic observables per site", Phys. Rev.
//       A 64, 032112 (2001); arXiv:quant-ph/0102024.
//       DOI 10.1103/PhysRevA.64.032112.
//       --> proves that the 2^{2^N} Bell-correlation inequalities for N
//           parties with two dichotomic observables per site can all be
//           written as a single LP polytope, and the BK operator M_N of
//           [3] is one of the extreme inequalities (the one saturated by
//           the GHZ state). Werner-Wolf §III explicitly states the
//           Tsirelson-type quantum maximum |<M_N>|_QM = 2^{(N-1)/2} for
//           the BK operator in the normalisation of [3], and gives the
//           optimal X/Y measurement on |GHZ_N> as the saturating
//           strategy.
//
//   [5] Daniel Cavalcanti, "Tight self-testing of multipartite Bell
//       inequalities via Renormalization-Group methods" (Abiuso, 2025;
//       arXiv:2503.03878). --> the RG-tight self-testing headline:
//           the MABK inequality (the operator M_N of [3]) self-tests the
//           N-party GHZ state up to local isometry from the violation
//           alone, with optimal noise tolerance, derived via a
//           renormalisation-group flow on the multipartite Bell
//           inequalities. Per the user task spec the paper is the
//           contextual citation; this module reproduces the EXACT
//           algebraic content (M_N as a sum of Pauli strings; <M_N>_GHZ
//           = 2^{(N-1)/2}; LHV brute force = 1; ratio = 2^{(N-1)/2}) at
//           N <= 6 -- the actual self-testing distance/isometry
//           reconstruction is OUT OF SCOPE for this module (would
//           require a robustness SDP; stated, never faked).
//
// ── BK recursion -> closed-form expansion (the operator this module computes) ─
//
//   The BK operator M_N is a linear combination of the 2^N length-N
//   Pauli strings sigma_{s_1} ⊗ ... ⊗ sigma_{s_N} with s_i in {X, Y}.
//   We carry the recursion as TWO sums (the unprimed M_N and the primed
//   M_N'), each represented as a flat float array indexed by the N-bit
//   string s (bit i = 0 -> sigma_X on qubit i, bit i = 1 -> sigma_Y).
//
//   On |GHZ_N> the Pauli-string expectation has the famous closed form
//        <GHZ_N| sigma_{s_1} ⊗ ... ⊗ sigma_{s_N} |GHZ_N>
//             =  0,             if (#Y in s) is odd
//             =  (-1)^{k/2},    if (#Y in s) = k is even
//   (derivation: sigma_X |0> = |1>, sigma_Y |0> = i|1>, sigma_X |1> =
//    |0>, sigma_Y |1> = -i|0>; on |0^N> the string returns i^k |1^N>,
//    on |1^N> it returns (-i)^k |0^N>; the GHZ inner product is then
//    (1/2)[i^k + (-i)^k] = 0 (k odd) or (-1)^{k/2} (k even).)
//
//   This module computes the GHZ expectation TWICE -- once via per-
//   string state-vector evolution + inner product (the engine_aer path;
//   the "EXACT 2^N UNITARY" claim) AND once via the closed-form Y-count
//   rule above (the algebraic cross-check); F1 falsifies if either
//   disagrees with 2^{(N-1)/2} by more than 1e-9.
//
// ── Honest scope (@D g1 / @D g3 / @F f1) ───────────────────────────────
//
//   - EXACT 2^N-amplitude UNITARY + projective sim on N in {3,4,5,6}.
//     2^6 = 64 amplitudes per state vector; well inside @D g1 (<=30q
//     state vector). No QRNG, no sampling, no shot noise -- the verdict
//     is the analytic Born-rule expectation of every Pauli string in
//     the BK polynomial, summed; the LHV bound is enumerated
//     deterministically over all 2^{2N} +-1 strategies (4096 at N=6),
//     evaluated by the bit-mask + popcount fast path (zero array
//     allocation in the hot loop -- the 0.1.0-dispatch interpreter
//     does not reclaim boxed numeric temporaries inside long while
//     loops, so the fast path is the difference between a finished
//     selftest and a 4GB RSS OOM).
//   - NOT a real-QPU MABK test. No detector-loophole closure, no
//     signaling-loophole closure, no spacelike-separation timing
//     argument. The DETECTOR / NO-SIGNALLING / FAIR-SAMPLING
//     assumptions are STANDARD nonlocality framework assumptions
//     (Mermin 1990 [1]; Ardehali 1992 [2]; BK 1993 [3]; Werner-Wolf
//     2001 [4]); NOT a hidden lattice-fit on any external entity
//     (@F f1).
//   - NOT a duplicate of qmirror/chsh: CHSH IS the N=2 case of MABK
//     (LHV bound 2, Tsirelson 2sqrt2, normalised ratio sqrt2 =
//     2^{(2-1)/2}); THIS module is the MULTIPARTITE generalisation
//     N in {3,4,5,6} with the EXPONENTIAL violation ratio
//     2^{(N-1)/2} (sqrt2, 2, 2sqrt2, 4) -- the headline that
//     distinguishes MABK from bipartite CHSH.
//   - NOT a duplicate of qmirror/ghz_mermin: ghz_mermin reproduces the
//     ALL-OR-NOTHING Mermin contradiction on a FIXED 4-basis witness
//     for N=3 (M = <XXX> - <XYY> - <YXY> - <YYX>, quantum 4 vs LHV 2);
//     THIS module reproduces the BELL-INEQUALITY version (continuous
//     violation magnitude via the BK operator, normalised LHV bound 1)
//     at every N in {3..6}, with the canonical BK recursive operator
//     of [3] rather than a hand-picked 4-string functional.
//   - NOT the Abiuso 2025 [5] self-testing DISTANCE / robust isometry
//     reconstruction: that would require a Navascues-Pironio-Acin
//     hierarchy SDP and a noise tolerance bound. This module
//     reproduces the EXACT algebraic content of the inequality
//     (operator, GHZ value, LHV bound, ratio) that Abiuso's RG
//     analysis self-tests; the self-testing reduction itself is
//     stated as out-of-scope, never faked.
//   - Governance: AGENTS.tape @D g1 (<=30q exact SV; here N<=6, well
//     inside), @D g5 (pure hexa, no .py / qiskit), @D g6 (falsifier-
//     first; FAILED-marker write path BEFORE pass path), @D g7
//     (engine_aer / qrng / chsh / iit_mip external sigs untouched).

use "../../engine_aer/module/state_vector.hexa"
use "../../engine_aer/module/gates.hexa"

// ── Public verdict struct ──────────────────────────────────────────────

struct MabkVerdict {
    ok:                  int,
    verdict:             str,         // "PASS" | "FAIL"
    // Per-N reproduced values (N=3..6) -- state-vector path
    b3_quantum:          float,       // <GHZ_3 | M_3 | GHZ_3>
    b3_closed:           float,       // 2^{(3-1)/2} = 2
    b4_quantum:          float,
    b4_closed:           float,       // 2^{(4-1)/2} = 2.828427...
    b5_quantum:          float,
    b5_closed:           float,       // 2^{(5-1)/2} = 4
    b6_quantum:          float,
    b6_closed:           float,       // 2^{(6-1)/2} = 5.656854...
    // Worst |sim - closed| over N=3..6 (F1 anchor; thresh 1e-9)
    max_q_dev:           float,
    f1_thresh:           float,
    f1_trip:             int,
    // LHV brute-force (F2; thresh 1e-9 -- analytic ±1 enumeration is exact)
    lhv_max_3:           float,       // max_a |M_3(a)| over 2^6 = 64 strategies
    lhv_max_4:           float,       // 2^8 = 256
    lhv_max_5:           float,       // 2^10 = 1024
    lhv_max_6:           float,       // 2^12 = 4096
    lhv_max_worst:       float,       // max over N
    f2_thresh:           float,
    f2_trip:             int,
    // Violation ratio Q_N = |B_N|^GHZ / |B_N|^LHV (F3 monotone; F4 N=6 > N=5)
    q3:                  float,
    q4:                  float,
    q5:                  float,
    q6:                  float,
    f3_trip:             int,         // monotone-increasing in N broken
    f4_trip:             int,         // Q6 < Q5 (anomalous decrease)
    // Norm drift (F5; thresh 1e-9)
    max_norm_drift:      float,
    f5_thresh:           float,
    f5_trip:             int,
    engine:              str,
    message:             str
}

fn _mabk_fail(reason: str) -> MabkVerdict {
    return MabkVerdict {
        ok: 0, verdict: "FAIL",
        b3_quantum: 0.0, b3_closed: 0.0,
        b4_quantum: 0.0, b4_closed: 0.0,
        b5_quantum: 0.0, b5_closed: 0.0,
        b6_quantum: 0.0, b6_closed: 0.0,
        max_q_dev: 0.0,
        f1_thresh: 0.000000001, f1_trip: 1,
        lhv_max_3: 0.0, lhv_max_4: 0.0, lhv_max_5: 0.0, lhv_max_6: 0.0,
        lhv_max_worst: 0.0,
        f2_thresh: 0.000000001, f2_trip: 1,
        q3: 0.0, q4: 0.0, q5: 0.0, q6: 0.0,
        f3_trip: 1, f4_trip: 1,
        max_norm_drift: 0.0,
        f5_thresh: 0.000000001, f5_trip: 1,
        engine: "none",
        message: reason
    }
}

// ── Numeric helpers ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────

fn _mabk_abs(x: float) -> float {
    if x < 0.0 { return 0.0 - x }
    return x
}

// Hot-loop friendly: hard-coded 2^k for k in {0..16} (well above any
// reachable bit-width here: N<=6 means N-bit string in [0,64), 2N-bit
// strategy in [0,4096), 8-bit mask in [0,256)). Avoids the 0.1.0-dispatch
// interpreter's per-call boxing overhead on the previous _mabk_pow2()
// helper -- profiled to be ~the dominant cost in the LHV inner loop.
fn _mabk_p2(k: int) -> int {
    if k == 0  { return 1 }
    if k == 1  { return 2 }
    if k == 2  { return 4 }
    if k == 3  { return 8 }
    if k == 4  { return 16 }
    if k == 5  { return 32 }
    if k == 6  { return 64 }
    if k == 7  { return 128 }
    if k == 8  { return 256 }
    if k == 9  { return 512 }
    if k == 10 { return 1024 }
    if k == 11 { return 2048 }
    if k == 12 { return 4096 }
    if k == 13 { return 8192 }
    if k == 14 { return 16384 }
    if k == 15 { return 32768 }
    return 65536
}

// Floating power 2^{(N-1)/2} (closed-form quantum max).
fn _mabk_quantum_max(big_n: int) -> float {
    let s = sqrt(2.0)
    let mut v = 1.0
    let mut k = 0
    let exp = big_n - 1
    while k < exp {
        v = v * s
        k = k + 1
    }
    return v
}

// Hamming popcount of a non-negative int via Kernighan's bit-strip
// (one iteration per SET bit; tight against the 0.1.0-dispatch
// interpreter's per-iter boxed-temporary growth -- max 12 iters at
// N=6 where strategy masks fit in 12 bits).
fn _mabk_popcount(x: int) -> int {
    let mut v = x
    let mut c = 0
    while v > 0 {
        v = v & (v - 1)
        c = c + 1
    }
    return c
}

// ── BK recursive operator expansion ────────────────────────────────────
//
// Carries M_N and M_N' as flat float arrays of length 2^N. String index
// s in [0, 2^N) encodes Pauli string with bit i (LSB = qubit 0) being
// 0 for sigma_X on qubit i and 1 for sigma_Y on qubit i.
//
// Recursion (BK, [3] of header):
//   M_1   = A_1   (= X on qubit 0)  -->  unp[s=0] = 1, unp[s=1] = 0
//   M_1'  = A_1'  (= Y on qubit 0)  -->  pri[s=0] = 0, pri[s=1] = 1
//   M_N   = (1/2)[ M_{N-1} (X_N + Y_N) + M_{N-1}' (X_N - Y_N) ]
//   M_N'  = (1/2)[ M_{N-1}' (X_N + Y_N) - M_{N-1} (X_N - Y_N) ]
//
// Step from level k to level k+1 (new qubit index = k):
//   for each old-string s_old (length k):
//     new_unp[s_old]                += (1/2)(old_unp[s_old] + old_pri[s_old])  // X_N
//     new_unp[s_old | 1<<k]         += (1/2)(old_unp[s_old] - old_pri[s_old])  // Y_N
//     new_pri[s_old]                += (1/2)(old_pri[s_old] - old_unp[s_old])
//     new_pri[s_old | 1<<k]         += (1/2)(old_pri[s_old] + old_unp[s_old])
//
// Returns [coeffs_unp, coeffs_pri] each of length 2^N.
fn _mabk_build_bk(big_n: int) -> [[float]] {
    if big_n < 1 { return [[], []] }
    let mut unp = [1.0, 0.0]      // M_1 = X
    let mut pri = [0.0, 1.0]      // M_1' = Y
    let mut k = 1
    while k < big_n {
        let old_len = _mabk_p2(k)
        let new_len = _mabk_p2(k + 1)
        let bit_mask = old_len
        let mut new_unp = []
        let mut new_pri = []
        let mut i = 0
        while i < new_len {
            new_unp = new_unp.push(0.0)
            new_pri = new_pri.push(0.0)
            i = i + 1
        }
        let mut s_old = 0
        while s_old < old_len {
            let u = unp[s_old]
            let p = pri[s_old]
            let idx_x = s_old
            let idx_y = s_old + bit_mask
            new_unp[idx_x] = new_unp[idx_x] + 0.5 * (u + p)
            new_unp[idx_y] = new_unp[idx_y] + 0.5 * (u - p)
            new_pri[idx_x] = new_pri[idx_x] + 0.5 * (p - u)
            new_pri[idx_y] = new_pri[idx_y] + 0.5 * (p + u)
            s_old = s_old + 1
        }
        unp = new_unp
        pri = new_pri
        k = k + 1
    }
    return [unp, pri]
}

// ── GHZ state preparation via engine_aer state_vector primitives ──────
//
// |GHZ_N> = (|0^N> + |1^N>) / sqrt(2) on N qubits via H_0 then chained
// CNOTs (0->1, 1->2, ..., N-2 -> N-1). qiskit endian: q0 = LSB.
fn _mabk_prepare_ghz_plain(big_n: int) -> StateVector {
    let h = gate_h()
    let st0 = state_zero(big_n)
    let mut s = apply_single(st0, h.re, h.im, 0, big_n)
    let mut q = 1
    while q < big_n {
        s = apply_cnot(s, q - 1, q, big_n)
        q = q + 1
    }
    return s
}

// ── Phase(phi) = diag(1, e^{i phi}) -- 1-qubit relative phase gate ────
//
// Applied to |1> of the chosen qubit it adds e^{i phi}; leaves |0>
// untouched. Identity tensor-applied across N qubits except on the
// chosen one. We use it on qubit (N-1) of |GHZ_N> to convert
//      (|0^N> + |1^N>) / sqrt(2)   into   (|0^N> + e^{i phi} |1^N>) / sqrt(2)
// which is the parameterised "rotated GHZ" needed to align the BK
// Pauli polynomial against the GHZ state (see "MABK saturation angle"
// derivation below).
fn _mabk_apply_phase(s: StateVector, q: int, big_n: int, phi: float) -> StateVector {
    let c = cos(phi)
    let sn = sin(phi)
    let g_re = [1.0, 0.0, 0.0, c]
    let g_im = [0.0, 0.0, 0.0, sn]
    return apply_single(s, g_re, g_im, q, big_n)
}

// ── MABK saturation angle phi_N* derived from the BK polynomial ───────
//
// On state |psi_phi> = (|0^N> + e^{i phi} |1^N>)/sqrt(2) the expectation
// of any Pauli string sigma_{s_1} ⊗ ... ⊗ sigma_{s_N} with s_i in {X, Y}
// depends only on k = #Y in s mod 4:
//      <S>_phi  =   cos(phi)    if k mod 4 == 0
//              =   sin(phi)    if k mod 4 == 1
//              =  -cos(phi)    if k mod 4 == 2
//              =  -sin(phi)    if k mod 4 == 3
// (Derivation: <psi_phi|S|psi_phi> = (i^k e^{-i phi} + (-i)^k e^{i phi})/2
//  = Re(i^k e^{-i phi}); evaluate at the four residues.)
//
// So <M_N>_phi = A cos(phi) + B sin(phi) with
//      A = Σ_{s: k≡0 (4)} coeff(s)  -  Σ_{s: k≡2 (4)} coeff(s)
//      B = Σ_{s: k≡1 (4)} coeff(s)  -  Σ_{s: k≡3 (4)} coeff(s)
// and the saturating phi is
//      phi_N* = atan2(B, A)         (gives <M_N>_{phi_N*} = sqrt(A^2 + B^2))
// with the known Werner-Wolf identity sqrt(A^2 + B^2) = 2^{(N-1)/2}.
//
// Returns [A, B, phi_star]. Pure float, no state vector.
fn _mabk_saturation_angle(big_n: int, coeffs: [float]) -> [float] {
    let dim_k = _mabk_p2(big_n)
    let mut a = 0.0
    let mut b = 0.0
    let mut s = 0
    while s < dim_k {
        let c = coeffs[s]
        let k = _mabk_popcount(s)
        let r = k % 4
        if r == 0 {
            a = a + c
        } else if r == 1 {
            b = b + c
        } else if r == 2 {
            a = a - c
        } else {
            b = b - c
        }
        s = s + 1
    }
    let phi = atan2(b, a)
    return [a, b, phi]
}

// |GHZ_N> rotated by Phase(phi_N*) on qubit (N-1) -- the state on which
// the BK polynomial M_N attains its quantum maximum 2^{(N-1)/2}.
fn _mabk_prepare_ghz(big_n: int, phi: float) -> StateVector {
    let s = _mabk_prepare_ghz_plain(big_n)
    return _mabk_apply_phase(s, big_n - 1, big_n, phi)
}

// ── State-vector helpers ───────────────────────────────────────────────

fn _mabk_norm2(s: StateVector) -> float {
    let dim = state_dim(s)
    let mut n2 = 0.0
    let mut i = 0
    while i < dim {
        let re = amp_re_at(s, i)
        let im = amp_im_at(s, i)
        n2 = n2 + re * re + im * im
        i = i + 1
    }
    return n2
}

// ── Pauli-string expectation on GHZ_N via state-vector evolution ──────
//
// <GHZ_N| sigma_{s_1} ⊗ ... ⊗ sigma_{s_N} |GHZ_N>  computed exactly:
// clone GHZ, apply each sigma in turn (X if bit=0, Y if bit=1), take the
// inner product Re[<GHZ|S|GHZ>]. The closed-form rule guarantees the
// imag part vanishes; F1 cross-checks via the closed-form path below.
fn _mabk_string_expectation_sv(psi: StateVector, s_idx: int, big_n: int,
                               gate_x_re: [float], gate_x_im: [float],
                               gate_y_re: [float], gate_y_im: [float]) -> float {
    let dim = state_dim(psi)
    let mut acted = state_clone(psi)
    let mut q = 0
    while q < big_n {
        let bit = (s_idx / _mabk_p2(q)) % 2
        if bit == 0 {
            acted = apply_single(acted, gate_x_re, gate_x_im, q, big_n)
        } else {
            acted = apply_single(acted, gate_y_re, gate_y_im, q, big_n)
        }
        q = q + 1
    }
    // <psi | acted> = sum_i conj(psi_i) * acted_i  (take the real part)
    let mut re_acc = 0.0
    let mut i = 0
    while i < dim {
        let pr = amp_re_at(psi, i)
        let pi = amp_im_at(psi, i)
        let ar = amp_re_at(acted, i)
        let ai = amp_im_at(acted, i)
        re_acc = re_acc + pr * ar + pi * ai
        i = i + 1
    }
    let _f = state_free(acted)
    return re_acc
}

// ── Pauli-string expectation on rotated GHZ via CLOSED FORM ────────────
//
// On |psi_phi> = (|0^N> + e^{i phi}|1^N>)/sqrt(2), the X/Y Pauli-string
// expectation (k = #Y) is
//      <S>  =   cos(phi)    if k mod 4 == 0
//           =   sin(phi)    if k mod 4 == 1
//           =  -cos(phi)    if k mod 4 == 2
//           =  -sin(phi)    if k mod 4 == 3
// (See _mabk_saturation_angle for the derivation.) Returns the value.
fn _mabk_string_expectation_closed(s_idx: int, phi: float) -> float {
    let k = _mabk_popcount(s_idx)
    let r = k % 4
    if r == 0 { return cos(phi) }
    if r == 1 { return sin(phi) }
    if r == 2 { return 0.0 - cos(phi) }
    return 0.0 - sin(phi)
}

// ── Compute <M_N>_GHZ via STATE VECTOR (linear combo of string exps) ──
//
// The "rotated GHZ" state (Phase(phi_N*) on qubit N-1 after the H+CNOT
// chain) is the saturating state for the BK polynomial M_N; see
// _mabk_saturation_angle. We compute <M_N>_{rotated GHZ} as Σ_s coeff_s
// * <S>_state via per-string state-vector evolution + inner product.
fn _mabk_value_sv(big_n: int, coeffs: [float], phi: float) -> float {
    let dim_k = _mabk_p2(big_n)
    let psi = _mabk_prepare_ghz(big_n, phi)
    let gx = gate_x()
    let gy = gate_y()
    let mut acc = 0.0
    let mut s = 0
    while s < dim_k {
        let c = coeffs[s]
        if _mabk_abs(c) > 0.0000000000001 {
            let e = _mabk_string_expectation_sv(psi, s, big_n, gx.re, gx.im, gy.re, gy.im)
            acc = acc + c * e
        }
        s = s + 1
    }
    let _f = state_free(psi)
    return acc
}

// ── Compute <M_N>_GHZ via CLOSED FORM (algebraic cross-check) ─────────
fn _mabk_value_closed(big_n: int, coeffs: [float], phi: float) -> float {
    let dim_k = _mabk_p2(big_n)
    let mut acc = 0.0
    let mut s = 0
    while s < dim_k {
        let c = coeffs[s]
        let e = _mabk_string_expectation_closed(s, phi)
        acc = acc + c * e
        s = s + 1
    }
    return acc
}

// ── Precompute the 2N-bit strategy-mask for each Pauli string ─────────
//
// For string s with bit i (=0 -> X, 1 -> Y), the LHV product
//     Π_i a_i^{(s_i)}
// where a_i^{(0)} ∈ {+1,-1} sits in strategy-bit (2i + 0) and a_i^{(1)}
// sits in strategy-bit (2i + 1) (0 -> +1, 1 -> -1), simplifies to
//     (-1)^popcount( strategy & m_s )
// where the mask m_s has bit (2i + s_i) set for every i in 0..N-1.
//
// We precompute m_s for every s once per N. Length-2^N int array.
fn _mabk_build_string_masks(big_n: int) -> [int] {
    let dim_k = _mabk_p2(big_n)
    let mut masks = []
    let mut s = 0
    while s < dim_k {
        let mut m = 0
        let mut i = 0
        while i < big_n {
            let s_bit = (s / _mabk_p2(i)) % 2     // 0 = X, 1 = Y
            let strat_bit_idx = 2 * i + s_bit
            m = m + _mabk_p2(strat_bit_idx)
            i = i + 1
        }
        masks = masks.push(m)
        s = s + 1
    }
    return masks
}

// ── LHV brute force: max |M_N(a)| over all 2^{2N} ±1 strategies ───────
//
// Each Pauli string product collapses to (-1)^popcount(t & m_s). We
// inline integer-only popcount in the inner loop to avoid the boxed-
// temporaries growth path of the 0.1.0-dispatch interpreter. (The
// previous Π_i a_i^{(s_i)} float-product path tripped the 4GB RSS
// cap during the N=6 brute force; this rewrite is allocation-free
// in the inner two loops and finishes in ~1 minute interpreted.)
//
// For the BK operator the LHV maximum is EXACTLY 1 by construction
// (the (1/2) factor at each recursion step cancels the doubling of the
// LHV bound -- Werner-Wolf 2001 [4] §III). The brute force confirms.
fn _mabk_lhv_max(big_n: int, coeffs: [float], masks: [int]) -> float {
    let dim_k = _mabk_p2(big_n)
    let total_strats = _mabk_p2(2 * big_n)
    let mut best = 0.0
    let mut t = 0
    while t < total_strats {
        let mut val = 0.0
        let mut s = 0
        while s < dim_k {
            let c = coeffs[s]
            // Native bitwise-AND + Kernighan popcount -- alloc-free
            let mut bits = t & masks[s]
            let mut parity = 0
            while bits > 0 {
                bits = bits & (bits - 1)
                parity = parity + 1
            }
            if (parity & 1) == 0 {
                val = val + c
            } else {
                val = val - c
            }
            s = s + 1
        }
        let av = if val < 0.0 { 0.0 - val } else { val }
        if av > best { best = av }
        t = t + 1
    }
    return best
}

// ── Top-level runner ───────────────────────────────────────────────────

fn mabk_ardehali_run() -> MabkVerdict {
    // BK coefficient tables (per N, computed once)
    let bk3 = _mabk_build_bk(3)
    let bk4 = _mabk_build_bk(4)
    let bk5 = _mabk_build_bk(5)
    let bk6 = _mabk_build_bk(6)
    let c3 = bk3[0]
    let c4 = bk4[0]
    let c5 = bk5[0]
    let c6 = bk6[0]

    // MABK saturating phases phi_N* = atan2(B_N, A_N) where
    //   A_N = Σ_{s: k%4==0} c_s - Σ_{s: k%4==2} c_s
    //   B_N = Σ_{s: k%4==1} c_s - Σ_{s: k%4==3} c_s
    // and sqrt(A^2 + B^2) = 2^{(N-1)/2} (the Werner-Wolf quantum max).
    let sat3 = _mabk_saturation_angle(3, c3)
    let sat4 = _mabk_saturation_angle(4, c4)
    let sat5 = _mabk_saturation_angle(5, c5)
    let sat6 = _mabk_saturation_angle(6, c6)
    let phi3 = sat3[2]
    let phi4 = sat4[2]
    let phi5 = sat5[2]
    let phi6 = sat6[2]

    // Norm drift: prep once per N, single norm2 read (on the rotated state).
    let psi3 = _mabk_prepare_ghz(3, phi3)
    let drift3 = _mabk_abs(_mabk_norm2(psi3) - 1.0)
    let _f3 = state_free(psi3)
    let psi4 = _mabk_prepare_ghz(4, phi4)
    let drift4 = _mabk_abs(_mabk_norm2(psi4) - 1.0)
    let _f4 = state_free(psi4)
    let psi5 = _mabk_prepare_ghz(5, phi5)
    let drift5 = _mabk_abs(_mabk_norm2(psi5) - 1.0)
    let _f5 = state_free(psi5)
    let psi6 = _mabk_prepare_ghz(6, phi6)
    let drift6 = _mabk_abs(_mabk_norm2(psi6) - 1.0)
    let _f6 = state_free(psi6)

    let mut max_drift = drift3
    if drift4 > max_drift { max_drift = drift4 }
    if drift5 > max_drift { max_drift = drift5 }
    if drift6 > max_drift { max_drift = drift6 }

    // <M_N>_{rotated GHZ} via state vector (the engine_aer 2^N UNITARY path)
    let b3_q = _mabk_value_sv(3, c3, phi3)
    let b4_q = _mabk_value_sv(4, c4, phi4)
    let b5_q = _mabk_value_sv(5, c5, phi5)
    let b6_q = _mabk_value_sv(6, c6, phi6)

    // <M_N>_{rotated GHZ} closed form (algebraic cross-check; cheap, kept for ALL N)
    let b3_c_alg = _mabk_value_closed(3, c3, phi3)
    let b4_c_alg = _mabk_value_closed(4, c4, phi4)
    let b5_c_alg = _mabk_value_closed(5, c5, phi5)
    let b6_c_alg = _mabk_value_closed(6, c6, phi6)

    // Closed-form quantum max 2^{(N-1)/2}
    let b3_c = _mabk_quantum_max(3)
    let b4_c = _mabk_quantum_max(4)
    let b5_c = _mabk_quantum_max(5)
    let b6_c = _mabk_quantum_max(6)

    // F1: |sim - 2^{(N-1)/2}| max over N (BOTH state-vector and algebraic must agree)
    let d3 = _mabk_abs(_mabk_abs(b3_q) - b3_c)
    let d4 = _mabk_abs(_mabk_abs(b4_q) - b4_c)
    let d5 = _mabk_abs(_mabk_abs(b5_q) - b5_c)
    let d6 = _mabk_abs(_mabk_abs(b6_q) - b6_c)
    let mut max_q_dev = d3
    if d4 > max_q_dev { max_q_dev = d4 }
    if d5 > max_q_dev { max_q_dev = d5 }
    if d6 > max_q_dev { max_q_dev = d6 }
    let alg_d3 = _mabk_abs(_mabk_abs(b3_c_alg) - b3_c)
    let alg_d4 = _mabk_abs(_mabk_abs(b4_c_alg) - b4_c)
    let alg_d5 = _mabk_abs(_mabk_abs(b5_c_alg) - b5_c)
    let alg_d6 = _mabk_abs(_mabk_abs(b6_c_alg) - b6_c)
    if alg_d3 > max_q_dev { max_q_dev = alg_d3 }
    if alg_d4 > max_q_dev { max_q_dev = alg_d4 }
    if alg_d5 > max_q_dev { max_q_dev = alg_d5 }
    if alg_d6 > max_q_dev { max_q_dev = alg_d6 }

    // F2: LHV brute force (must equal 1 to 1e-9 by BK construction)
    let m3 = _mabk_build_string_masks(3)
    let m4 = _mabk_build_string_masks(4)
    let m5 = _mabk_build_string_masks(5)
    let m6 = _mabk_build_string_masks(6)
    let lhv3 = _mabk_lhv_max(3, c3, m3)
    let lhv4 = _mabk_lhv_max(4, c4, m4)
    let lhv5 = _mabk_lhv_max(5, c5, m5)
    let lhv6 = _mabk_lhv_max(6, c6, m6)
    let mut lhv_worst = lhv3
    if lhv4 > lhv_worst { lhv_worst = lhv4 }
    if lhv5 > lhv_worst { lhv_worst = lhv5 }
    if lhv6 > lhv_worst { lhv_worst = lhv6 }

    // Violation ratios Q_N = |<M_N>|^GHZ / |<M_N>|^LHV
    let q3 = _mabk_abs(b3_q) / lhv3
    let q4 = _mabk_abs(b4_q) / lhv4
    let q5 = _mabk_abs(b5_q) / lhv5
    let q6 = _mabk_abs(b6_q) / lhv6

    // Thresholds (analytic Born-rule + ±1 enumeration; everything tight)
    let f1_thresh = 0.000000001            // 1e-9
    let f2_thresh = 0.000000001            // 1e-9 (LHV must equal 1 exactly)
    let f5_thresh = 0.000000001            // 1e-9

    let f1_trip = if max_q_dev > f1_thresh { 1 } else { 0 }
    let lhv_dev = _mabk_abs(lhv_worst - 1.0)
    let f2_trip = if lhv_dev > f2_thresh { 1 } else { 0 }
    let mut f3_trip = 0
    if q4 <= q3 { f3_trip = 1 }
    if q5 <= q4 { f3_trip = 1 }
    if q6 <= q5 { f3_trip = 1 }
    let f4_trip = if q6 < q5 { 1 } else { 0 }
    let f5_trip = if max_drift > f5_thresh { 1 } else { 0 }

    let trips = f1_trip + f2_trip + f3_trip + f4_trip + f5_trip
    let pass = trips == 0

    let msg = "N=3 B=" + str(b3_q) + " (closed=" + str(b3_c) + ")" +
              " ; N=4 B=" + str(b4_q) + " (closed=" + str(b4_c) + ")" +
              " ; N=5 B=" + str(b5_q) + " (closed=" + str(b5_c) + ")" +
              " ; N=6 B=" + str(b6_q) + " (closed=" + str(b6_c) + ")" +
              " ; max_q_dev=" + str(max_q_dev) +
              " ; lhv_worst=" + str(lhv_worst) +
              " ; Q3=" + str(q3) +
              " ; Q4=" + str(q4) +
              " ; Q5=" + str(q5) +
              " ; Q6=" + str(q6) +
              " ; max_drift=" + str(max_drift) +
              " ; trips=" + str(trips)

    return MabkVerdict {
        ok: 1,
        verdict: if pass { "PASS" } else { "FAIL" },
        b3_quantum: b3_q, b3_closed: b3_c,
        b4_quantum: b4_q, b4_closed: b4_c,
        b5_quantum: b5_q, b5_closed: b5_c,
        b6_quantum: b6_q, b6_closed: b6_c,
        max_q_dev: max_q_dev,
        f1_thresh: f1_thresh, f1_trip: f1_trip,
        lhv_max_3: lhv3, lhv_max_4: lhv4, lhv_max_5: lhv5, lhv_max_6: lhv6,
        lhv_max_worst: lhv_worst,
        f2_thresh: f2_thresh, f2_trip: f2_trip,
        q3: q3, q4: q4, q5: q5, q6: q6,
        f3_trip: f3_trip, f4_trip: f4_trip,
        max_norm_drift: max_drift,
        f5_thresh: f5_thresh, f5_trip: f5_trip,
        engine: "hexa_native",
        message: msg
    }
}

// ── Falsifier-first marker emission (@D g6) ────────────────────────────
//
// FAILED-suffix is the control-flow default (the failure suffix is
// installed BEFORE the pass suffix), then -- and only then -- the pass
// path overrides the suffix iff every F1..F5 invariant holds. Matches
// the hardy-multipartite / pseudo-telepathy-doily pattern.

fn _mabk_emit_marker(passed: int, body: str) -> int {
    let ts = exec("date +%s").trim()
    let qm_root = env("QMIRROR_ROOT")
    let root = if qm_root.len() > 0 { qm_root } else { exec("pwd").trim() }
    let marker_dir = root + "/state/markers"
    let _mk = exec("mkdir -p " + marker_dir + " 2>/dev/null")
    let mut suffix = "_FAILED.marker"
    if passed == 1 { suffix = ".marker" }
    let path = marker_dir + "/mabk_ardehali_" + ts + suffix
    let _w = exec("echo '" + body + "' > '" + path + "'")
    println("  marker: " + path)
    return 0
}

// ── Public selftest ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

fn selftest() -> MabkVerdict {
    return mabk_ardehali_run()
}

fn main() {
    println("[qmirror/mabk-ardehali] Mermin-Ardehali-Belinskii-Klyshko (MABK) multipartite Bell inequality")
    println("  papers: Mermin 1990 PRL 65 1838 (original N-party Bell-GHZ inequality, Eq.4-5)")
    println("          Ardehali 1992 PRA 46 5375 (exponential 2^{(N-1)/2} violation for all N)")
    println("          Belinskii-Klyshko 1993 PhysUsp 36 653 (BK recursive form, normalisation LHV=1)")
    println("          Werner-Wolf 2001 PRA 64 032112 / quant-ph/0102024 (Tsirelson |<M_N>|=2^{(N-1)/2})")
    println("          Abiuso 2025 arXiv:2503.03878 (RG-tight self-testing -- contextual; self-test")
    println("                                         DISTANCE / robust isometry OUT OF SCOPE here)")
    println("  caveat: EXACT 2^N-amplitude (N in {3,4,5,6}) UNITARY+projective sim;")
    println("          NO QRNG / NO sampling / NO real-QPU device noise;")
    println("          NO detector-loophole / NO signaling-loophole closure")
    println("          (standard MABK framework assumptions, NOT a lattice-fit).")
    println("          Distinct from CHSH (N=2 case; ratio sqrt2) and from ghz_mermin")
    println("          (all-or-nothing fixed-4-basis Mermin contradiction for N=3 only).")
    println("")

    let v = mabk_ardehali_run()
    if v.ok != 1 {
        let _ = _mabk_emit_marker(0, "FAIL " + v.message)
        println("  ERROR: " + v.message)
        println("[qmirror/mabk-ardehali] SELFTEST FAIL (run error)")
        println("__QMIRROR_MABK_ARDEHALI__ FAIL")
        return
    }

    println("  Reproduced <M_N>_GHZ vs closed-form 2^{(N-1)/2}:")
    println("    N=3 : sim=" + str(v.b3_quantum) + "   closed=" + str(v.b3_closed))
    println("    N=4 : sim=" + str(v.b4_quantum) + "   closed=" + str(v.b4_closed))
    println("    N=5 : sim=" + str(v.b5_quantum) + "   closed=" + str(v.b5_closed))
    println("    N=6 : sim=" + str(v.b6_quantum) + "   closed=" + str(v.b6_closed))
    println("    max |dev| over N = " + str(v.max_q_dev) + "   (F1 thresh 1e-9)")
    println("")
    println("  LHV brute-force max |M_N(a)| over all 2^{2N} +-1 strategies:")
    println("    N=3 : " + str(v.lhv_max_3) + "   (64 strategies)")
    println("    N=4 : " + str(v.lhv_max_4) + "   (256 strategies)")
    println("    N=5 : " + str(v.lhv_max_5) + "   (1024 strategies)")
    println("    N=6 : " + str(v.lhv_max_6) + "   (4096 strategies)")
    println("    worst = " + str(v.lhv_max_worst) + "   (must be 1.0 to 1e-9; F2 thresh)")
    println("")
    println("  Violation ratio Q_N = |B_N|^GHZ / |B_N|^LHV  (must be monotone-increasing):")
    println("    Q_3 = " + str(v.q3) + "   (closed 2          = 2)")
    println("    Q_4 = " + str(v.q4) + "   (closed 2*sqrt(2)  = 2.82843...)")
    println("    Q_5 = " + str(v.q5) + "   (closed 4          = 4)")
    println("    Q_6 = " + str(v.q6) + "   (closed 4*sqrt(2)  = 5.65685...)")
    println("")
    println("  Norm drift on |GHZ_N> (max over N): " + str(v.max_norm_drift) +
            "   (F5 thresh 1e-9)")
    println("")
    println("  Falsifier verdicts:")
    println("    F1 (max |B_N - 2^{(N-1)/2}| < 1e-9)   : " +
            (if v.f1_trip == 0 { "PASS" } else { "FAIL" }))
    println("    F2 (LHV brute-force max <= 1 + 1e-9)  : " +
            (if v.f2_trip == 0 { "PASS" } else { "FAIL" }))
    println("    F3 (Q_N monotone increasing in N)     : " +
            (if v.f3_trip == 0 { "PASS" } else { "FAIL" }))
    println("    F4 (Q_6 >= Q_5)                       : " +
            (if v.f4_trip == 0 { "PASS" } else { "FAIL" }))
    println("    F5 (GHZ norm drift < 1e-9)            : " +
            (if v.f5_trip == 0 { "PASS" } else { "FAIL" }))
    println("  verdict = " + v.verdict)
    println("")

    let pass = v.verdict == "PASS"
    let _ = _mabk_emit_marker(if pass { 1 } else { 0 },
                              (if pass { "PASS " } else { "FAIL " }) + v.message)
    if pass {
        println("[qmirror/mabk-ardehali] SELFTEST PASS")
        println("  (BK operator <M_N>_GHZ = 2^{(N-1)/2} reproduced to 1e-9 on the")
        println("   engine_aer state-vector kernel for N in {3,4,5,6}; LHV brute force")
        println("   confirms |M_N|^LHV = 1 exactly; exponential violation Q_N = 2^{(N-1)/2}")
        println("   monotone-increasing -- the Mermin-Ardehali exponential gap reproduced.)")
        println("__QMIRROR_MABK_ARDEHALI__ PASS")
    } else {
        println("[qmirror/mabk-ardehali] SELFTEST FAIL (falsifier triggered)")
        println("__QMIRROR_MABK_ARDEHALI__ FAIL")
    }
}
